{"title_page": "Papa Don't Preach", "text_new": "{{short description|1986 single by Madonna}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Papa Don't Preach\n| cover      = Madonna, Papa Don't Preach cover.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| album      = [[True Blue (Madonna album)|True Blue]]\n| B-side     = Pretender\n| released   = June 11, 1986\n| format     =\n*[[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n*[[12-inch single|12\"]]\n*[[CD single|CD]]\n*[[CD Video|video]]\n| recorded   = 1985\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = 4:29\n| label      =\n* [[Sire Records|Sire]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     =\n*Brian Elliot\n*[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| producer   =\n* Madonna\n* [[Stephen Bray]]\n| prev_title = [[Live to Tell]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[True Blue (Madonna song)|True Blue]]\n| next_year  = 1986\n}}\n\n\"'''Papa Don't Preach'''\" is a song by American singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] from her third studio album ''[[True Blue (Madonna album)|True Blue]]'' (1986). The song was written by Brian Elliot with additional lyrics by Madonna, who produced it with [[Stephen Bray]]. The song also appears [[remix]]ed on the 1990 compilation album ''[[The Immaculate Collection]]'' and in its original form on the 2009 compilation album ''[[Celebration (Madonna album)|Celebration]]''. The song's musical style combines pop and classical styling, and its lyrics deal with [[teenage pregnancy]] and the choices that come with it. It was based on teen gossip Elliot heard outside his recording studio.\n\nReleased as the album's second single in mid-1986, the song was a commercial success. It became Madonna's fourth number-one single on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and performed well internationally, reaching the top position in the United Kingdom and Australia. It was well received by music critics and was frequently cited as a highlight in the album. The music video, directed by [[James Foley (director)|James Foley]], shows Madonna's second image makeover, featuring her with a more toned and muscular body, and cropped [[Blond|platinum blonde]] hair. It portrayed a storyline where Madonna is trying to tell her father about her pregnancy. The images are juxtaposed with shots of Madonna dancing and singing in a small, darkened studio, and spending a romantic evening with her boyfriend.\n\nShortly after its release, the song caused heated discussions about its lyrical content. Women's organizations and others in the family planning field criticized Madonna for encouraging teenage pregnancy, while groups opposed to abortion saw the song as having a positive [[anti-abortion]] message. Madonna has performed \"Papa Don't Preach\" in five of her world tours, the latest being the [[Madame X Tour]] in 2019. The song also caused her first conflict with the [[Holy See|Vatican]], as she dedicated it to [[Pope John Paul II]], who urged Italian fans to boycott her concerts during the [[Who's That Girl World Tour]] in 1987. In 2002, British singer [[Kelly Osbourne]] recorded a [[hard rock]] cover of the song which was included as a bonus track on her debut album ''[[Shut Up (Kelly Osbourne album)|Shut Up]]''.\n\n==Writing and inspiration==\nDuring the autumn of 1985, Madonna started writing and recording songs for her third studio album, ''[[True Blue (Madonna album)|True Blue]]''. She brought back [[Stephen Bray|Steve Bray]] and hired a new producer, [[Patrick Leonard]], to help her on the album.<ref>{{harvnb|Cross|2007|pp=40\u201341}}</ref> The album's first track \"Papa Don't Preach\", was written by Brian Elliot, who described it as \"a love song, maybe framed a little bit differently\".<ref name=\"stpetersburg\">{{cite journal|issn=1563-6291|title='Papa Don't Preach' Stirs Teen Pregnancy Debate|date=September 5, 1986|journal=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|publisher=[[Times Publishing Company]]|ref=harv}}</ref> The song is based on teen gossip he heard outside his recording studio, which has a large front window that doubles as a mirror where schoolgirls from the [[North Hollywood High School]] in Los Angeles regularly stopped to fix their hair and chat.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gossip Composite|date=September 18, 1986|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|publisher=[[A. H. Belo|A. H. Belo Corporation]]}}</ref> The song was sent to Madonna by Michael Ostin, the same [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] executive who discovered \"[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\".<ref name=\"metz\">{{harvnb|Metz|Benson|1999|p=48}}</ref> Madonna only contributed with some additional lyrics, making \"Papa Don't Preach\" the only song on the album that she did not have a strong hand in writing.<ref name=\"metz\"/> In 2009, during an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' Madonna was asked by the interviewer Austin Scaggs as to why the theme of the song was meaningful to her. She replied saying,\n<blockquote>\n[The song] just fit right in with my own personal zeitgeist of standing up to male authorities, whether it's the pope, or the Catholic Church or my father and his conservative, patriarchal ways.&nbsp;... For 'Papa Don't Preach' there were so many opinions&nbsp;\u2013 that's why I thought it was so great. Is she for 'schma-smortion', as they say in ''[[Knocked Up]]''? Is she against abortion?<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/readers-poll-the-best-madonna-videos-of-all-time-20120829/10-papa-dont-preach-0035837|last=Scaggs|first=Austin|date=October 29, 2009|title=Madonna Looks Back: The Rolling Stone Interview|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Jann Wenner}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Composition==\n{{listen\n | pos         = right\n | filename    = Madonna_- papa don't preach.ogg\n | title       = \"Papa Don't Preach\"\n | description = A 27 second sample from \"Papa Don't Preach\", featuring Madonna singing in a pleading voice, with a backing track that combines pop and classical music.\n | format      = [[Ogg]]\n }}\n\"Papa Don't Preach\" is a [[dance-pop]] song with instrumentation from [[Steel-string acoustic guitar|acoustic]], [[Electric guitar|electric]], and [[rhythm guitar]]s, [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], and [[string section|string arrangement]]s. It is set in [[Time signature|common time]], and moves at a moderate [[tempo]] of 116 [[Tempo|beats per minute]].<ref name=\"musicsheet\">{{cite web|title=Digital Sheet Music: Papa Don't Preach|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0037601|work=Musicnotes|publisher=[[Alfred Music Publishing|Alfred Publishing Co. Inc]]}}</ref> The song is written in the key of [[F minor]]. The combination of key and tempo produces a disjuncture between pop and classical rhythms, underlined by the instrumentation during the [[Introduction (music)|introduction]].<ref name=\"fouz\">{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|p=61}}</ref>\n\nThe song begins with a distinctly [[Antonio Vivaldi|Vivaldian]] style, as the fast tempo and classical-style [[chord progression]] anticipates the lyrics to follow. The opening chords and the melody emphasize the tonic of the leading notes: Fm\u2013E{{music|flat}}\u2013D{{music|flat}}\u2013Cm\u2013D{{music|flat}}\u2013E{{music|flat}}\u2013Fm\u2013D{{music|flat}}\u2013E{{music|flat}}\u2013Fm, resembling a [[Baroque music|Baroque]] work. This is followed by the sound of [[dance music]], produced by a powerful beat from the instruments.<ref name=\"fouz\"/> Madonna's [[vocal range]] spans from F<sub>3</sub> to C<sub>5</sub>,<ref name=\"musicsheet\"/> and has a different sound from her previous work, more mature, centered, and with a lower range.<ref name=\"fouz\"/>\n\nThe lyrics show Madonna's interest in her [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] upbringing, as the song theme is about a girl who tells her father that she is pregnant and refuses to have an abortion or give up the baby for adoption despite what her friends are telling her to do.<ref>{{harvnb|Bielen|1999|p=151}}</ref> It is constructed in a [[verse-chorus form]], with a [[Bridge (music)|bridge]] before the third and final chorus. At the beginning, she addresses her father directly, asking him to talk to her as an adult, \"You should know by now that I'm not a baby\". The transition to the chorus employs a more dramatic voice with a higher range, ending nearly in cries as she sings the word \"Please\". Leading to the chorus, Madonna switches to a pleading voice, singing the song's main [[Hook (music)|hook]] in a high tone. During the bridge, the song features a Spanish-inspired rhythm, one of the earliest examples of the influence that [[Latin American music|Hispanic music]] had on Madonna's musical style.<ref name=\"fouz\"/>\n\n==Critical response==\n[[File:Madonna II A 13 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Madonna performing the track during the [[Who's That Girl World Tour]] (1987).]]\n\"Papa Don't Preach\" was met with acclaim from music critics. [[Davitt Sigerson]] from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine in a review of the album ''[[True Blue (Madonna album)|True Blue]]'' said that if there is a problem with the album \"it's the lack of outstanding songs\", adding that \"only the magnificent 'Papa Don't Preach' has the high-profile hook to match 'Like a Virgin', '[[Dress You Up]]' and '[[Material Girl]]'.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Davitt|last=Sigerson|authorlink=Davitt Sigerson|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/reviews/album/7076/36379|title=Madonna: True Blue: Music Reviews|date=July 17, 1986|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=RealNetworks, Inc|accessdate=February 26, 2009}}</ref> In its review of ''True Blue'', [[Allmusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] said that \"she is using the music to hook in critics just as she's baiting a mass audience with such masterstrokes as 'Papa Don't Preach'.\"<ref>{{Cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=True Blue > Overview|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r12205|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=February 26, 2009}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] in a review for ''[[The Village Voice]]'' felt that \"she [Madonna] doesn't speak for the ordinary teenaged stiff any more than [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]] speaks for the union members\", adding that \"while the antiabortion content of 'Papa Don't Preach' isn't unequivocal, and wouldn't make the song bad by definition if it were, the ambiguity is a cop-out rather than an open door, which is bad.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Robert |last=Christgau |authorlink=Robert Christgau |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=madonna |title=Consumer Guide Reviews: Madonna |publisher=Robert Christgau.com |accessdate=February 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSal Cinquemani from ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' said that \"with songs like 'Papa Don't Preach', Madonna made the transition from pop tart to consummate artist, joining the ranks of 80s icons like [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Prince (musician)|Prince]].\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Sal|last=Cinquemani|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/american-idol-20-years-of-madonna|title=American Idol: 20 Years of Madonna|year=2003|magazine=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=February 26, 2009}}</ref> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' in a review of her first compilation album ''[[The Immaculate Collection]]'', commented that \"In theory, a 30-ish urban sophisticate singing in the voice of a pregnant teen [...] ought to sound ridiculous\", but added that \"With the help of collaborators like [[Stephen Bray]] and [[Patrick Leonard]], though, [the song] turns into a perfectly conceived pop record.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|title=Music Review: The Immaculate Collection (1990)|url=https://ew.com/article/1990/12/14/immaculate-collection/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=December 14, 1990|accessdate=February 26, 2009}}</ref> In 2005, the same magazine placed the song at number 486 on its list of \"The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/doc/420485618.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep%2015,%202005&author=&pub=Chicago%20Tribune&edition=&startpage=&desc=X%20and%20Y%20playlist|title=X and Y playlist: The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born |author=Blender staff|date=April 1, 2009|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=Tribune Company|accessdate=July 20, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017220013/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/doc/420485618.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep%2015,%202005&author=&pub=Chicago%20Tribune&edition=&startpage=&desc=X%20and%20Y%20playlist|archivedate=October 17, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1987, the song was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]] at the [[29th Grammy Awards]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Hunt|first=Dennis|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/58214434.html?dids=58214434:58214434&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+09%2C+1987&author=DENNIS+HUNT&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=GRAMMY+NOMINATIONS%3A+HIGHS+AND+LOWS+Winwood%2C+Gabriel+and+Simon+Garner+Most+Nominations&pqatl=google|title=Grammy Nominations: Highs and Lows Winwood, Gabriel and Simon Garner Most Nominations|date=January 9, 1987|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722172817/https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/58214434.html?dids=58214434:58214434&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+09%2C+1987&author=DENNIS+HUNT&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=GRAMMY+NOMINATIONS%3A+HIGHS+AND+LOWS+Winwood%2C+Gabriel+and+Simon+Garner+Most+Nominations&pqatl=google|archivedate=July 22, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> but lost to [[Barbra Streisand]]'s ''[[The Broadway Album]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Barbra&field_nominee_work_value=&year=1986&genre=24&=Search|title=Grammy Awards Winners: The Broadway Album|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Papa Don't Preach\" was released in the United States in June 1986. It debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 42<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1986-06-28/hot-100?order=gainer|title=The Billboard Hot 100: Week Ending June 28, 1986 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|date=June 28, 1986|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> and, within eight weeks of release, reached the top of the chart, making it Madonna's fourth number-one single in the US. It maintained the top position for two weeks and spent 18 weeks on the chart.<ref name=\"bbhot100\"/> It also reached a peak of four on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] chart and a peak of number 16 on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart.<ref name=\"dance\"/><ref name=\"ac\"/> In October 1998, the single was certified [[Music recording sales certification|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for shipment of a million copies of the single.<ref name=\"riaa\"/> It placed at position 29 for the ''Billboard'' Year-End chart for 1986.<ref name=\"bbyearend\">{{cite journal|title=Top Pop Singles|volume=98|issue=52|date=December 27, 1986|issn=0006-2510|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tiQEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 4, 2011|journal=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media}}</ref> In Canada the song debuted at number 53 of the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' singles chart on July 5, 1986,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0695&volume=44&issue=15&issue_dt=July%2005%201986&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 0695|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|publisher=RPM Music Publications Ltd|accessdate=February 25, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309190310/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0695&volume=44&issue=15&issue_dt=July%2005%201986&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=March 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> reached the top for two weeks in August 1986,<ref name=\"canrpm\"/> and stayed on the chart for 20 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0856&volume=45&issue=8&issue_dt=November%2015%201986&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 0856|work=RPM|publisher=RPM Music Publications Ltd|accessdate=February 25, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707103622/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0856&volume=45&issue=8&issue_dt=November%2015%201986&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=July 7, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> It placed at position 13 on the ''RPM'' Year-End chart for 1986.<ref name=\"rpmyearend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0760&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top 100 Singles of '86|date=December 27, 1986|accessdate=August 26, 2010|work=RPM|publisher=RPM Music Publications Ltd|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018052844/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0760&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 18, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Papa Don't Preach\" was released on June 16, 1986. The song debuted at number 13 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] before climbing to number one two weeks later. It then spent three consecutive weeks at the top, stayed 15 weeks on the chart,<ref name=\"uk\"/> and was certified gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) in August 1986 for shipment of 500,000 copies of the single.<ref name=\"bpi\"/> According to the [[Official Charts Company]], the song has sold 650,700 copies in the UK by August 2016.<ref name=\"uksales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/madonna-s-official-top-40-biggest-selling-singles__8266/|title=Open your chart to me... Madonna's Official Top 40 Biggest Selling Singles|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=August 16, 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAcross Europe, \"Papa Don't Preach\" was successful, topping the [[European Hot 100 Singles|Eurochart Hot 100]] for 11 weeks.<ref name=\"euro\"/> It reached the top position of the singles charts in Belgium, Ireland, and Norway,<ref name=\"belfla\"/><ref name=\"irl\"/><ref name=\"nor\"/> and peaked inside the top five in Austria, France, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain and Switzerland.<ref name=\"ger\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/title/MADONNA/Papa+Don%2527t+Preach/single|title=Chartverfolgung > Madonna > Papa Don't Preach|language=German|publisher=[[Media Control Charts]]|date=August 18, 1986|accessdate=February 24, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129124439/http://musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/title/MADONNA/Papa+Don%2527t+Preach/single|archive-date=November 29, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"dt40\"/><ref name=\"spain\">{{cite book |last=Salaverri|first=Fernando|title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002|edition=1st |date=September 2005|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Autor-SGAE|location=Spain|isbn=84-8048-639-2}}</ref><ref name=\"swi\"/>\n\nThe song also reached the top of the charts in Australia, and inside the Top 5 in South Africa and New Zealand.\n\n==Music video==\n[[File:Madonnapapadon'tpreachmusicvideo.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Refer to caption|Madonna in a scene from the music video, sporting the gamine look. She stands in the hallway during the tension with her father (in the distance) after telling him about her pregnancy.]]\nFor the music video, Madonna sported a complete image [[makeover]]. She changed the heavy jewelry and make-up, and adopted the [[gamine]] look, which is notably applied to describe the style and appearance that [[Shirley MacLaine]] and [[Audrey Hepburn]] used during the 1950s.<ref>{{harvnb|Voller|1999|p=24}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=62}}</ref> In the video Madonna played a [[tomboy]], dressed in jeans, a black leather jacket, and a [[T-shirt#Expressive messages|slogan T-shirt]] with the caption \"Italians do it better\". The video alternated between tomboy shots and those of a more glamorous Madonna with a more toned and muscular body, cropped [[Blond|platinum blonde]] hair, and figure-revealing clothing, consisting of a 1960s-style black bustier top and [[capri pants]].<ref name=\"mansour\">{{harvnb|Mansour|2005|p=352}}</ref>\n\nThe video was directed by [[James Foley (director)|James Foley]], who worked with Madonna in her music video for \"[[Live to Tell]]\",<ref>{{harvnb|Metz|Benson|1999|p=309}}</ref> produced by David Naylor and [[Sharon Oreck]], and [[Michael Ballhaus]] was in charge of the photography.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[The Immaculate Collection (video)|The Immaculate Collection]]|medium= VHS|publisher=[[Warner Music Vision]]|date=1990}}</ref> The video was shot on location over three days in Staten Island, New York and Manhattan. Staten Island was chosen on Foley's suggestion as it was where he grew up: \"We talked about wanting to tap into a working-class environment, because by that time she had done 'Material Girl' and 'Like a Virgin' and other stuff that was very glamorous and stylized. She wanted to do something a bit more grounded and 'drama'.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/making-of-madonnas-20-best-music-videos-20150225/papa-dont-preach-1986-20150224|title=Papa Don't Preach: The Making of Madonna's 20 Greatest Music Videos|last=Johnston|first=Maura|date=February 24, 2015|accessdate=May 27, 2016|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> Actor [[Alex McArthur]] was signed to play Madonna's boyfriend and the father of her child in the video. Madonna had spotted McArthur in a small role as a naive youth in the 1985 film ''[[Desert Hearts]]'', and she thought he was a natural to play her mechanic boyfriend. \"I was out in the garage working on my Harley,\" said McArthur, \"I answered the phone and a voice said, 'Hi, this is Madonna. I would like you to be in my next video.'\"<ref name=\"people\"/>\n\nThe music video starts with shots of the [[New York City|New York]] skyline, the [[Staten Island Ferry]], and character close-ups.<ref name=\"mitchell\">{{harvnb|Mitchell|2000|p=15}}</ref> Madonna is seen walking along a lane. Then it shows her thinking about her father, played by actor [[Danny Aiello]],<ref name=\"mansour\"/> and how much he loves her. She then sees her boyfriend, played by actor [[Alex McArthur]],<ref name=\"people\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20094280,00.html|title=Alex McArthur's Silent Sizzling in a Video with Madonna Has Women Crying 'Who's That?'|date=August 11, 1986|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|accessdate=February 27, 2009}}</ref> coming along. The images are juxtaposed with shots of a more glamorous Madonna dancing and singing in a small, darkened studio. Madonna then moves away from her friends, who warn her about her boyfriend. She and her boyfriend spend a romantic evening together on a barge where they reflect upon their lives after watching an elderly couple. Madonna then finds out that she is pregnant and decides to keep the baby. After much hesitation, she tells her father and he's shocked and leaves the room to think about the situation, and eventually accepts the pregnancy.  Afterward, father and daughter hug each other.<ref name=\"mitchell\"/>\n\nGeorges-Claude Guilbert, author of ''Madonna as Postmodern Myth'', compared her look in the video as a \"combination of [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Jean Seberg]] and [[Kim Novak]].\" He added that it was hard for him to believe that \"[Madonna] did not know that she was going to cause a huge controversy with the video&nbsp;... With such a song and video, she was throwing in America's face the image of a country ravaged by the abortion debate, which is far from being resolved.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Guilbert|2002|p=169}}</ref> Lynda Hart, one of the authors of ''Acting Out: Feminist Performances'', felt that the video \"alternated between two competing representations of Madonna&nbsp;... Charging coercion, both sides make the video as an invitation to a certain way of life, in the process denying it the stylistic invocation of a rhetoric of self-authorization.\"<ref name=\"Hart 1993 348\">{{harvnb|Hart|Phelan|1993|p=348}}</ref> At the [[1987 MTV Video Music Awards]], the \"Papa Don't Preach\" video won the [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Female Video|Best Female Video]] award, and was nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Overall Performance|Best Overall Performance]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1987/|title=MTV Video Music Awards&nbsp;\u2013 1987|date=September 11, 1987|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[MTV Networks]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\n[[File:Papa Don't Preach Seattle.jpg|thumb|Madonna performing a shortened version of \"Papa Don't Preach\" during [[The MDNA Tour]] in 2012.]]\nMadonna has performed the song on four of her world tours. She premiered the song in 1987, during her [[Who's That Girl World Tour]], where she danced around the stage wearing a white Spanish-style dress designed by Marlene Stewart,<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=66}}</ref> and a black leather jacket similar to the one she used in the music video. The screen in the background showed portraits of [[Pope John Paul II]] and then-President of the US [[Ronald Reagan]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Kogan|first=Rick|authorlink=Rick Kogan|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/24651867.html?dids=24651867:24651867&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Aug+02%2C+1987&author=Rick+Kogan&pub=Chicago+Tribune+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=BOMBSHELL+MADONNA+CERTAINLY+CAN+WOW+'EM&pqatl=google|title=Bombshell Madonna Certainly Can Wow 'Em|date=August 2, 1987|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=March 3, 2009}}</ref> along with scenes of John Perry III's short film, ''The Nightmare'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Patrick|authorlink=Patrick Goldstein|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/58418158.html?dids=58418158:58418158&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+26%2C+1987&author=PATRICK+GOLDSTEIN&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=POP+EYE&pqatl=google|title=Pop Eye on Madonna|date=July 26, 1987|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=March 3, 2009}}</ref> ending with the words \"Safe Sex\", as Madonna finished the song.<ref>{{harvnb|Kellner|1995|p=276}}</ref> She dedicated the song to the Pope, marking her first conflict with the [[Holy See|Vatican]], as Pope John Paul II urged Italian fans to boycott her concerts.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farber|first=Jim|title=When it comes to controversy on tour, Madonna's been down this road|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/2008/10/22/2008-10-22_when_it_comes_to_controversy_on_tour_mad.html|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]|date=October 22, 2008|accessdate=March 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Madge through the years|url=https://www.usatoday.com/printedition/life/20081016/d_madonna16_timeline.art.htm|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|accessdate=March 8, 2009 | date=October 15, 2008}}</ref> Two different performances of the song on this tour can be found on the videos: ''Who's That Girl: Live in Japan'', filmed in [[Tokyo]], Japan, on June 22, 1987,<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Who's That Girl: Live in Japan|medium=VHS|publisher=Warner-Pioneer Japan|date=1987}}</ref> and ''[[Ciao Italia: Live from Italy]]'', filmed in [[Turin]], Italy, on September 4, 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Phares|first=Heather|title=Ciao Italia: Live in Italy (Video) > Overview |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r86678|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=March 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThree years later on her [[Blond Ambition World Tour]] in 1990, Madonna evoked Catholic images during the \"Papa Don't Preach\" performance. She wore a black [[kaftan]] made of chiffon and energetically danced, accompanied by six male dancers, with a platform full of [[votive candle]]s in the background.<ref name=\"yokohama\"/> Two different performances were taped and released on video, the ''Blond Ambition Japan Tour 90'', taped in [[Yokohama]], Japan, on April 27, 1990,<ref name=\"yokohama\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Blond Ambition Japan Tour 90|medium=VHS|publisher=Warner-Pioneer Japan|date=1990}}</ref> and the ''[[Blond Ambition World Tour Live]]'', taped in [[Nice]], France, on August 5, 1990.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[Blond Ambition World Tour Live]]|medium=Laserdisc|publisher=Pioneer Artists|date=1990}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, during the [[Re-Invention World Tour]], Madonna performed the song wearing a Scottish [[kilt]], and a T-shirt that said \"Kabbalists do it Better\" on most of the shows, and \"Brits do it Better\" and \"Irish do it Better\" T-shirts during the shows in the United Kingdom and Ireland, reminiscent of the one she used in the song's music video.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gundersen|first=Edna|title=Madonna: The mother of Reinvention|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2004-05-25-madonna-tour_x.htm|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|accessdate=March 3, 2009 | date=May 25, 2004}}</ref> Madonna also performed a shorter, abbreviated version of \"Papa Don't Preach\" on [[The MDNA Tour]] in 2012. Wearing a black tight outfit, Madonna sang the song while crawling around on the ground, then towards the end of the performance, several dancers wearing military clothing and animal masks surrounded and tied her up and took her to the main stage, giving way to the next performance, \"[[Hung Up]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Fensterstock|first=Alison|title=Thrills and chills from Madonna, in an epic set at the New Orleans Arena Saturday night|url=http://www.nola.com/music/index.ssf/2012/10/thrills_and_chills_from_madonn.html|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|date=October 28, 2012|accessdate=March 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Fiorillo|first=Victor|title=Madonna Gets Booed by, Then Stuns Philadelphia|url=http://blogs.phillymag.com/the_philly_post/2012/08/29/draft-draft-madonna-booed-stuns-philadelphia/|magazine=[[Philadelphia (magazine)|The Philly Post]]|date=August 29, 2012|accessdate=March 22, 2013}}</ref> The song was part of the set list for Madonna's all-theatre tour, [[Madame X Tour]].\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{See also|List of cover versions of Madonna songs|List of Madonna tribute albums}}\n[[File:Kelly Osbourne 2013.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Kelly Osbourne]]'s cover of the song became a commercial success]]\n\"Papa Don't Preach\" has been covered by numerous artists.\n\n===Kelly Osbourne version===\nIn 2002, British singer [[Kelly Osbourne]] recorded a [[hard rock]] cover of the song with [[Incubus (band)|Incubus]] members [[Mike Einziger]] (on guitar) and [[Jos\u00e9 Pasillas]] (on drums); the cover was produced by her brother [[Jack Osbourne]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Corey|last=Moss|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453639/20020426/index.jhtml?headlines=true|title=Kelly Osbourne's Ready For Her Closeup With 'Papa Don't Preach' Video|date=April 29, 2002|publisher=MTV (MTV Networks)|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> Osbourne's cover was included as a bonus track on her debut album ''[[Shut Up (Kelly Osbourne album)|Shut Up]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Shut Up (Bonus Track) > Overview|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r908571|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> and on the [[The Osbourne Family Album|soundtrack]] of [[MTV]]'s [[reality television]] program ''[[The Osbournes]]''<ref>{{cite web|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=The Osbourne Family Album > Album Review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r594241|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> and was released as her debut single.\n\nThe single was released in the United Kingdom in September 2002, peaking at number three.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/kelly%20osbourne/|title=Artist Chart History: Kelly Osbourne|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> In the rest of Europe, the song peaked inside the top ten in Ireland and Finland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Kelly+Osbourne|title=Kelly Osbourne&nbsp;\u2013 Discography|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://finnishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Kelly+Osbourne&titel=Papa+Don%27t+Preach&cat=s|title=Kelly Osbourne&nbsp;\u2013 Papa Don't Preach (Song)|publisher=[[YLE]]|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> and the top twenty in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Kelly+Osbourne&titel=Papa+Don%27t+Preach&cat=s|title=Kelly Osbourne&nbsp;\u2013 Papa Don't Preach (Song)|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|date=August 22, 2002|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> In Australia, the song debuted at number three,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Kelly+Osbourne&titel=Papa+Don%27t+Preach&cat=s|title=Kelly Osbourne&nbsp;\u2013 Papa Don't Preach (Song)|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> and received a platinum certification by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA).<ref name=\"aria\"/> Osbourne's version was panned by music critics, who thought that the cover \"makes precisely zero sense\", and that it \"reeks of opportunism\", also criticizing Incubus' collaboration, describing it as \"unimaginative\", and that \"their presence makes the whole mess barely distinguishable\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Brunner|first=Rob|title=Music Capsule Review: Papa Don't Preach|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,254407,00.html|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=June 3, 2002|accessdate=February 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Peter|last=Robinson|authorlink=Peter Robinson (journalist)|title=Kelly Osbourne featuring Incubus : Papa Don't Preach|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/6691|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|date=September 2, 2002|accessdate=February 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Other versions===\nIn 1986, [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] included the song as the last in his polka medley \"[[List of \"Weird Al\" Yankovic polka medleys#Polka Party!|Polka Party!]]\" from his [[Polka Party!|album of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Yankovic |first=Alfred M. |title=Parodies & Polkas |url=http://www.weirdal.com/parodypolkas.htm |publisher=The Official \"Weird Al\" Yankovic Web Site |accessdate=June 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070113231432/http://www.weirdal.com/parodypolkas.htm |archivedate=January 13, 2007 }}</ref> French group Mad'House made a [[Eurodance]] cover of the song, that was included on their 2002 album ''Absolutely Mad''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Absolutely Mad > Overview|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r606622|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> Covers of the song on tribute albums include Brook Barros on ''The Music of Madonna'', released in 2005,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Music of Madonna > Overview|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r1219410|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> and a jazz version on Bo. Da's '' Plays Madonna in Jazz'', released in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Plays Madonna in Jazz > Overview|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r1039414|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> The song has been sampled at the beginning of [[Mario Winans]]' 2004 single \"Never Really Was\", and a slowed-down version by [[Keshia Chant\u00e9]] sample the song in the 2006 single \"Fallen\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/find_out/specials/reviews/newsid_3591000/3591466.stm|title=Single: Mario Winans&nbsp;\u2013 Never Really Was|date=August 31, 2004|publisher=[[CBBC]]. [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=February 25, 2009}}</ref> In 2001, [[Picturehouse (band)|Picturehouse]] released a quiet acoustic cover on the first ''[[Even Better Than the Real Thing]]'' covers album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covermesongs.com/2010/08/they-say-its-your-birthday-madonna.html|title=They Say Its Your Birthday Madonna|date=August 9, 2010|accessdate=August 17, 2010|publisher=Cover Me Songs}}</ref> [[Dianna Agron]] from the television show ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' released an acoustic cover of the songs as her character [[Quinn Fabray]], a pregnant teenager, in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/958444/glees-madonna-powers-to-no-1-on-billboard-200|title=Glee's 'Madonna' Powers To No. 1 On Billboard 200 |date=April 28, 2010|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|accessdate=June 25, 2010}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Madonna's Re-Invention in Paris 3.jpg|upright|thumbnail|Madonna wearing a [[kilt]], performs \"Papa Don't Preach\" on the [[Re-Invention World Tour]] in 2004]]\nAs the song's popularity increased in the United States, so did the criticism and support it received from groups concerned with [[pregnancy]] and [[abortion]]. In July 1986, shortly after the release of the video for \"Papa Don't Preach\", Madonna commented on the controversy surrounding the song, to music critic [[Stephen Holden]] from ''[[The New York Times]]'':<ref name=\"metz\"/>\n<blockquote>\n\"Papa Don't Preach\" is a message song that everyone is going to take the wrong way. Immediately they're going to say I am advising every young girl to go out and get pregnant. When I first heard the song, I thought it was silly. But then I thought, wait a minute, this song is really about a girl who is making a decision in her life. She has a very close relationship with her father and wants to maintain that closeness. To me it's a celebration of life. It says, 'I love you, father, and I love this man and this child that is growing inside me'. Of course, who knows how it will end? But at least it starts off positive.\n</blockquote>\n\nPeople who criticized the song's message included [[Ellen Goodman]], a national syndicated [[columnist]], who called the video \"a commercial for [[teenage pregnancy]]\".<ref>{{harvnb|Hart|Phelan|1993|p=347}}</ref> Feminist lawyer [[Gloria Allred]], the spokeswoman of the [[National Organization for Women]] (NOW), angrily called for Madonna to make a public statement or another record supporting the opposite point of view.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF50FD8A0950E46&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Music-Rock News & Notes|date=September 12, 1986|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|accessdate=February 28, 2009}}</ref> Alfred Moran, the executive director of [[Planned Parenthood|Planned Parenthood of New York City]], also criticized the song, fearing that it would undermine efforts to promote [[birth control]] among adolescents and that it would encourage teenage pregnancy. Recalling how his agency's clinics were filled in 1985 with girls wearing clothes that were an imitation of [[Madonna wannabe|Madonna's style]], Moran said that the song's message is \"that getting pregnant is cool and having the baby is the right thing and a good thing and don't listen to your parents, the school, anybody who tells you otherwise\u2014don't preach to me, Papa. The reality is that what Madonna is suggesting to teenagers is a path to permanent poverty.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Singer|2002|p=405}}</ref><ref name=\"newyorktimes\">{{cite news|first=Georgia|last=Dullea|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/18/nyregion/madonna-s-new-beat-is-a-hit-but-song-s-message-rankles.html?sec=health&spon=&pagewanted=all|title=Madonna's New Beat is a Hit, but Song's Message Rankles|date=September 18, 1986|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=February 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast, groups opposed to abortion saw \"Papa Don't Preach\" as a positive, [[anti-abortion]] song. Susan Carpenter-McMillan, the president of the California chapter of [[Feminists for Life]] (FFL) in the US, said that \"abortion is readily available on every street corner for young women. Now what Madonna is telling them is, hey, there's an alternative.\"<ref name=\"newyorktimes\"/> [[Tipper Gore]], a founder of the [[Parents Music Resource Center]] (PMRC), who a year earlier denounced Madonna for the sexual lyrical content of her single \"Dress You Up\",<ref>{{harvnb|Denisoff|1988|p=299}}</ref> and had led a campaign against explicit content in music,<ref>{{harvnb|Thompson|2007|p=18}}</ref> commended Madonna for speaking candidly about such a serious subject and important social issue. When speaking of the song, Gore said \"the song speaks to a serious subject with a sense of urgency and sensitivity in both the lyrics and Madonna's rendition. It also speaks to the fact that there's got to be more support and more communication in families about this problem, and anything that fosters that I applaud.\" <ref name=\"newyorktimes\"/>\n\nThe song's writer, Brian Elliot, commented about the debate: \"I just wanted to make this girl in the song a sympathetic character. As a father myself, I'd want to be accessible to my children's problems.\"<ref name=\"stpetersburg\"/> Madonna avoided the controversy, and did not comment on the song's use as a pro-life statement. Her publicist, Liz Rosenberg, said that \"she [Madonna] is singing a song, not taking a stand\", adding that \"her philosophy is people can think what they want to think.\"<ref name=\"Hart 1993 348\"/><ref name=\"newyorktimes\"/> Danny Aiello, having appeared in the video as the titular \"Papa\", recorded \"Papa Wants the Best for You\" later that year, an [[answer song]] written by [[Artie Schroeck]] from the father's point of view.<ref>{{cite news|first=Liz |last=Smith|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19861022&id=jmoeAAAAIBAJ&pg=6710,2137407 |title=Papa Gets Second Chance In New Video|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|date=October 22, 1986|page=5E|accessdate=November 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing and formats==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n*'''7\" single (US)'''<ref name=\"Papa Don\u2019t Preach\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Papa Don\u2019t Preach|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|date=1986|type=US 7-inch Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=728660}}</ref>\n#\"Papa Don't Preach\" (LP Version)&nbsp;\u2013 4:27\n#\"Pretender\" (LP Version)&nbsp;\u2013 4:28\n\n*'''7\" single (UK)'''<ref name=\"Papa Don\u2019t Preach\"/>\n#\"Papa Don't Preach\" (LP Version)&nbsp;\u2013 4:27\n#\"Ain't No Big Deal\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:12\n\n*'''7\" single (Japan)'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Papa Don\u2019t Preach|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|date=1986|type=Japanese 7-inch Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=9205030}}</re